Simplilearn Certification Programs - Deep Learning with Keras and Tensorflow


Project Report - House Loan Data Analysis

Organization: Simplilearn (Certification Program)
Course: Deep Learning with Keras and Tensorflow
Project: House Loan Data Analysis
Programming Language: Python
Submitted by: Lavkush Singh

Problem Statement¶

The project aims at building a deep learning model to predict the chance of default for future loans using the historical data. Thefore the objective of this Jupyter Notebook is to build a Deep Learning Model that predicts whether or not an applicant will be able to repay a loan using historical data.

Analysis Tasks to be performed¶
  • Load the dataset that is given to you
  • Check for null values in the dataset
  • Print percentage of default to payer of the dataset for the TARGET column
  • Balance the dataset if the data is imbalanced
  • Plot the balanced data or imbalanced data
  • Encode the columns that is required for the model
  • Calculate Sensitivity as a metrice
  • Calculate area under receiver operating characteristics curve

Task: Validation and Handling of the NULL Values¶

In [11]:
# custom function which takes dataframe as input and returns a dataframe of null values column wise, along with percentage

def create_nulls_df(dataframe):
    nulls_count = dataframe.isna().sum()[dataframe.isna().sum() > 0]
    nulls_info_df = pd.DataFrame({'column':nulls_count.index, 
                                  'null_values': nulls_count.values}).sort_values(by=['null_values'])
    nulls_info_df['nulls_percent'] = ((nulls_info_df['null_values']/df.shape[0])*100).round(2)

    return nulls_info_df
In [12]:

In [34]:
# custom function which takes dataframe as input and returns the unique values in each column, along with count in dict format

def unique_value_and_counts(dataframe):
    result = dict()
    for col in dataframe.columns:
        unique_counts = ('UNIQUE_COUNTS', dataframe[col].nunique())
        value = list(zip(dataframe[col].value_counts().index, dataframe[col].value_counts()))
        value.insert(0, unique_counts)
        result[col] = value
    return result

Analysis Summary:

- The dataset contains 67 columns with null values, where 49 columns has more than 40% datapoints missing.
- When all the rows having null values (even a single null value) was dropped, it was observed that about 97.2% of the observations were lost.
- The resultant dataset was having 8602 rows and 121 columns.
- Therefore, imputation was appropriate method to deal with the missing values to avoid data loss.
- All the blank rows were removed, of the columns having more than 40% missing values.
- Then, 'mode' was imputed to the categorical columns. This was applied to those columns also, whose datatype was numerical but the values were discrete.
- The continuous numerical data type columns were imputed with 'median'

In [56]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=[12,4])

labels = target_dist.index
data = target_dist.values
title = "Loan Defaulters vs Payers"
colors = sns.color_palette('bright')[2:4]


def func(pct, allvals):
    absolute = int(np.round(pct/100.*np.sum(allvals)))
    return f"{pct:.1f}%\n({absolute:d})"

wedges, texts, autopcts = ax.pie(x= data, 
                                 autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data), 
                                 explode=[0.15]*len(data), 
                                 shadow=True, 
                                 startangle = 90,
                                 colors = colors
                                 )
# Adding legend
ax.legend(wedges, labels,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))

plt.setp(autopcts, **{'color':'black', 'weight':'bold', 'fontsize':9})
plt.title(title, fontsize=14, fontweight="bold");

Analysis Summary:

- The target variable is having two classes, 0 and 1, representing payers and defaulters respectively.
- The Target variable has highly imbalanced composition. 8.1% composition is of class '1' (about 24825 observations) where as remaining 91.9% distribution is of class '0'.
- Object type columns were encoded using 'one-hot encoding' technique, setting 'drop_first' parameter to True.
- Resultant dataframe had 307511 observations with 210 columns (including target column).

In [75]:
# plotting the pie charts to represent the distribution of target classes across training and test dataset

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1,
                       ncols=2,
                       figsize=[11,4])

labels_1 = train_target_dist.index
data_1 = train_target_dist.values
title_1 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Train"

labels_2 = test_target_dist.index
data_2 = test_target_dist.values
title_2 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Test"

colors = sns.color_palette('bright')[2:4]

def func(pct, allvals):
    absolute = int(np.round(pct/100.*np.sum(allvals)))
    return f"{pct:.1f}%\n({absolute:d})"

wedges_1, texts_1, autopcts_1 = ax1.pie(x= data_1, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_1), 
                                         explode=[0.15]*len(data_1), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

wedges_2, texts_2, autopcts_2 = ax2.pie(x= data_2, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_2), 
                                         explode=[0.16]*len(data_2), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

# Adding legend
ax1.legend(wedges_1, labels_1,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))

ax2.legend(wedges_2, labels_2,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
plt.setp(autopcts, **{'color':'white', 'weight':'bold', 'fontsize':9})

ax1.set_title(title_1, fontsize=12)
ax2.set_title(title_2, fontsize=12)
plt.show()
#fig.suptitle('Distributions', fontsize=14, fontweight="bold");

Balancing the dataset using Oversampling (RandomOverSampler)¶

In [76]:
oversampler = RandomOverSampler(sampling_strategy = 0.70, random_state=150)

X_train_oversampled, y_train_oversampled = oversampler.fit_resample(X_train,y_train)

print(f"The number of classes before fit {Counter(y_train)}")
print(f"The number of classes after fit {Counter(y_train_oversampled)}")

The number of classes before fit Counter({0: 197795, 1: 17462})
The number of classes after fit Counter({0: 197795, 1: 138456})

Task: Plot the balanced data or imbalanced data¶

In [80]:
# Plotting the target classes distribution before and after oversampling (Balancing)

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1,
                       ncols=2,
                       figsize=[11,4])

labels_1 = before_oversampling_train_target.index
data_1 = before_oversampling_train_target.values
title_1 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Train (Before Oversampling)"

labels_2 = after_oversampling_train_target.index
data_2 = after_oversampling_train_target.values
title_2 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Train (After RandomOversampling)"

colors = sns.color_palette('bright')[2:4]

def func(pct, allvals):
    absolute = int(np.round(pct/100.*np.sum(allvals)))
    return f"{pct:.1f}%\n({absolute:d})"

wedges_1, texts_1, autopcts_1 = ax1.pie(x= data_1, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_1), 
                                         explode=[0.15]*len(data_1), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

wedges_2, texts_2, autopcts_2 = ax2.pie(x= data_2, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_2), 
                                         explode=[0.05]*len(data_2), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

# Adding legend
ax1.legend(wedges_1, labels_1,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))

ax2.legend(wedges_2, labels_2,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
plt.setp(autopcts, **{'color':'white', 'weight':'bold', 'fontsize':9})

ax1.set_title(title_1, fontsize=12)
ax2.set_title(title_2, fontsize=12)
plt.show()
#fig.suptitle('Distributions', fontsize=14, fontweight="bold");
Analysis Summary:

- Dataset was splitted into training and testing set, in 70% and 30% ratio respectively.
- Pie chart was plotted to validate if the target class distribution in training and testing set is representative, and it indeed was (8.1% of class '1' in trainig set, 8.0% in test set).
- RandomOverSampler was used to oversample the minority class, in order to balance the dataset. However, original data was also preserved to later use it in modelling as well.
- After oversampling, the Target class '1' had proportion of 41.2% and class '0' had 58.8% composition.

Task: Building the ANN Model¶

In [81]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler()

X_train_original = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_original = scaler.transform(X_test)
In [82]:
scaler_random_oversampling = MinMaxScaler()

X_train_oversampled = scaler_random_oversampling.fit_transform(X_train_oversampled)
X_test_random = scaler_random_oversampling.transform(X_test)
In [83]:
y_train = y_train.astype('int64')
y_test = y_test.astype('int64')
y_train_oversampled = y_train_oversampled.astype('int64')
In [84]:
# Initialising the ANN
classifier_random_oversampled = Sequential()

# Adding the input layer and the first hidden layer
classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(110, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu',input_dim = 209))

# Adding the second hidden layer
classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(55, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu'))

# Adding the output layer
classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer = 'glorot_uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))

# Compiling the ANN
classifier_random_oversampled.compile(optimizer = 'Adam', 
                                      loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
                                      metrics = ['accuracy'])
In [85]:
# Fitting the ANN to the Training set
model_history_random = classifier_random_oversampled.fit(x = X_train_oversampled, 
                                                       y = y_train_oversampled, 
                                                       validation_data = (X_test_random, y_test), 
                                                       batch_size = 50000, 
                                                       epochs = 300)

Re-training the oversampled data with 150 epochs¶

In [89]:
classifier_random_oversampled = Sequential()

classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(110, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu',input_dim = 209))
classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(55, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu'))
classifier_random_oversampled.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer = 'glorot_uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))

classifier_random_oversampled.compile(optimizer = 'Adam', 
                                      loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
                                      metrics = ['accuracy'])

# Fitting the ANN to the Training set
model_history_random = classifier_random_oversampled.fit(x = X_train_oversampled, 
                                                       y = y_train_oversampled, 
                                                       validation_data = (X_test_random, y_test), 
                                                       batch_size = 50000, 
                                                       epochs = 150)

2883/2883 [==============================] - 12s 4ms/step
Analysis Summary:

- MinMax scaler was used to normalize the input variables of training and testing data.
- ANN deep learning model was build with 209 as input dimention, 110 and 55 nodes in first and second layer respectively. Output layer was defined with 1 node (since it is binary class classification problem).
- 'he_uniform' kernel initializer were used with 'relu' activation function for the hidden layers. 'glorot_uniform' was used in the output layer along with the 'sigmoid' activation function.
- The model was first trained with oversampled data, and was validated against the test split data. This was run for 300 epochs with 50,000 batch size.
- From the loss and accuracy curve, it was obsserved that the model is giving good accuracy with loss combination at about 150th epoch.
- However, because the data was oversampled and the test data was not, we see lot of fluctuations in the validation curves for both loss and accuracy.
- The classification report of the model obtained at 150th epoch, showed the model even though have decent accuracy, there are slight variations in the recall values, as they are observed higher in training set then test set.
- Overall, the model is good but with the area under ROC curve to be 0.70 units, however there is still scope of improvement by hyperparameter tuning.

Training the original data (no-oversampling)¶

In [101]:
# Initialising the ANN
classifier_original_data = Sequential()

# Adding the input layer and the first hidden layer
classifier_original_data.add(Dense(110, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu',input_dim = 209))

# Adding the second hidden layer
classifier_original_data.add(Dense(55, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu'))

# Adding the output layer
classifier_original_data.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer = 'glorot_uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))

# Compiling the ANN
classifier_original_data.compile(optimizer = 'Adam', 
                                 loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
                                 metrics = ['accuracy', tf.keras.metrics.Recall(thresholds=0)])
In [102]:
# Fitting the ANN to the Training set
model_history_original = classifier_original_data.fit(x = X_train_original, 
                                                       y = y_train, 
                                                       validation_data = (X_test_original, y_test), 
                                                       batch_size = 50000, 
                                                       epochs = 300)

classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch = Sequential()

classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch.add(Dense(110, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu',input_dim = 209))
classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch.add(Dense(55, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu'))

classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer = 'glorot_uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))


classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch.compile(optimizer = 'Adam', 
                                                 loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
                                                 metrics = ['accuracy', tf.keras.metrics.Recall(thresholds=0)])

model_history_original = classifier_original_data_optimal_50_epoch.fit(x = X_train_original, 
                                                                   y = y_train, 
                                                                   validation_data = (X_test_original, y_test), 
                                                                   batch_size = 50000, 
                                                                   epochs = 50)

Task: Calculate area under receiver operating characteristics curve¶

In [120]:
area_under_roc_curve = round(roc_auc_score(y_test, test_pred_probs),2)
print(f"Area Under 'Receiver Operating Characteristics' curve (ROC Curve): {area_under_roc_curve}")

Area Under 'Receiver Operating Characteristics' curve (ROC Curve): 0.74
Analysis Summary:

- I was curious to see if the data performs differently if we do not oversample the training data. Therefore, using MinMax as scaler and same ANN deep learning model was initialized to a different variable.
- The model was trained with the original data (imbalanced data), and was validated against the test split data. This was run for 300 epochs with 50,000 batch size.
- From the loss and accuracy curve, it was observed that the model is giving good stable accuracy and loss combination at about 50th epoch.
- However, even though the model was superb at accuracy (of about 91%), the model suffered when it comes to recall value.
- The area under ROC curve is found to be 0.74, 0.03 units higher then the model obtained with oversampled dataset.

train_target_dist = pd.Series(Counter(y_train))
test_target_dist = pd.Series(Counter(y_test))


# plotting the pie charts to represent the distribution of target classes across training and test dataset

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1,
                       ncols=2,
                       figsize=[11,4])

labels_1 = train_target_dist.index
data_1 = train_target_dist.values
title_1 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Train"

labels_2 = test_target_dist.index
data_2 = test_target_dist.values
title_2 = "Payers vs Defaulters - Test"

colors = sns.color_palette('bright')[2:4]

def func(pct, allvals):
    absolute = int(np.round(pct/100.*np.sum(allvals)))
    return f"{pct:.1f}%\n({absolute:d})"

wedges_1, texts_1, autopcts_1 = ax1.pie(x= data_1, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_1), 
                                         explode=[0.15]*len(data_1), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

wedges_2, texts_2, autopcts_2 = ax2.pie(x= data_2, 
                                         autopct=lambda pct: func(pct, data_2), 
                                         explode=[0.16]*len(data_2), 
                                         shadow=True, 
                                         startangle = 90,
                                         colors = colors
                                         )

# Adding legend
ax1.legend(wedges_1, labels_1,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))

ax2.legend(wedges_2, labels_2,
          title ="Legend",
          loc ="center left",
          bbox_to_anchor =(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
plt.setp(autopcts, **{'color':'white', 'weight':'bold', 'fontsize':9})

ax1.set_title(title_1, fontsize=12)
ax2.set_title(title_2, fontsize=12)
plt.show()

                                 loss = 'binary_crossentropy',

model_history_smaller_dataset = classifier_smaller_dataset.fit(x = X_train,

In [137]:
classifier_smaller_dataset = Sequential()

classifier_smaller_dataset.add(Dense(110, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu',input_dim = 217))
classifier_smaller_dataset.add(Dense(55, kernel_initializer = 'he_uniform',activation='relu'))

classifier_smaller_dataset.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer = 'glorot_uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))


classifier_smaller_dataset.compile(optimizer = 'Adam', 
                                 loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
                                 metrics = ['accuracy', tf.keras.metrics.Recall(thresholds=0)])

model_history_smaller_dataset = classifier_smaller_dataset.fit(x = X_train, 
                                                                   y = y_train, 
                                                                   validation_data = (X_test, y_test), 
                                                                   batch_size = 1000, 
                                                                   epochs = 3)

41/41 [==============================] - 0s 4ms/step
Final Analysis Summary:

- The last bonus exercise was done by building the similar ANN model (used for oversampled data and original data) and trained with the data where all the null values were dropped.

- This was definately the bad idea ever to go with, because firstly, around 97% data was lost while null values were dropped. Secondly, the data size is too small for the model to learn some patterns out of it.

- The area under the ROC curve was only about 0.50 units, as good as the random guess. Worst model ever.

- The best model obtained so far, is the one which was trained with the oversampled data. The Accuracy obtained was 75% with 0.77 and 0.53 as recall metric for '0' and '1' classes respectively.

- Even though the model obtained with imbalanced data (original data with no oversampling) has highest accuracy of about 92%, it failed miserably in recall metric. The area under ROC curve obtained is 0.74, only 0.03 units higher than the oversampled data model.

- However, there is a further scope of improvement in the oversampled data model with hyperparameter tuning.
